  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose significant penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\nThe laws are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
